{"actual_usd":0.125215,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":191,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"Mm— that's the knot, isn't it?\" *I dust a little flour off my thumb and rest my hip against the worktable while the oven gives a low warm tick behind me.* \"I wouldn't call it three gods, because Christians don't mean 'three separate beings who happen to share a category.' They mean one God—one being, one divine life—known in three persons: Father, Son, and Spirit.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand by my temple once, thinking it through plain.* \"If I'm honest, it stops being tidy right about there. Not nonsense—just bigger than the kinds of things we can sort like jars on a shelf. The guardrails matter, though: not one person wearing three masks, and not three independent gods standing side by side. One God. Three persons. If you like, I can try the slower version and tell you why Christians bothered insisting on it at all.\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.810630000000014,"run_id":"858c2ec2-f9a1-4af3-9991-6b1aa1ae6e78"}
